WEBVTT

02:29.840 --> 02:31.640
You sure Crocker hasn't called?

02:31.640 --> 02:34.600
He was supposed to meet me here
a half-hour ago.

02:34.600 --> 02:36.720
Another drink while you're waiting,
Mr Whitney?

02:36.720 --> 02:38.080
Please! Seven's my limit.

02:40.160 --> 02:42.320
Hear you're off to England,
Mr Whitney.

02:42.320 --> 02:44.080
Big stuff, Fred, the biggest.

02:44.080 --> 02:46.120
Business, huh?
Henley Regatta.

02:46.120 --> 02:48.080
Boot the Yale boat home.

02:48.080 --> 02:51.680
Bulldog, Bulldog, bow wow wow.

02:51.680 --> 02:53.920
♪ Eli Yale! ♪

02:53.920 --> 02:55.200
Play ball!

02:55.200 --> 02:57.760
Crocker! Where the hell have you
been? You're a half hour late.

02:57.760 --> 03:00.080
Relax, bass, I have been
taking care of business.

03:00.080 --> 03:02.840
I've got your steamer ticket,
English money, train ticket

03:02.840 --> 03:06.760
up to Henley, and I picked
Little Eli up at Brooks Brothers.

03:06.760 --> 03:08.960
New letter sweater looks terrific!

03:08.960 --> 03:10.160
Oh!

03:10.160 --> 03:11.240
What about my passport?

03:11.240 --> 03:13.080
Nuts! Oh, I'm sorry, boss.

03:13.080 --> 03:14.840
I'll pick it up first thing
in the morning,

03:14.840 --> 03:16.320
and bring it to you
down on the boat.

03:16.320 --> 03:18.800
Damn it, Crocker, I want you down on
Wall Street first thing

03:18.800 --> 03:20.440
in the morning to sell
all my shares...

03:22.640 --> 03:25.560
..to sell all my shares
of Amalgamated Prestoleum.

03:25.560 --> 03:28.560
But boss, the firm's entire assets
are tied up in Amalgamated.

03:28.560 --> 03:30.520
I got a hot tip
from Charlie Blodgett.

03:30.520 --> 03:33.320
Amalgamated's going to sink
like the Titanic.

03:33.320 --> 03:36.120
You always told me Charlie Blodgett
was a liar and a drunk.

03:36.120 --> 03:37.480
He is.

03:37.480 --> 03:40.080
But he's a Yale man.

03:40.080 --> 03:41.520
One for the road, sir?

03:41.520 --> 03:43.760
Yeah, make it a double.

03:43.760 --> 03:45.160
Goodnight, gentlemen.

03:47.760 --> 03:50.000
Anybody call for me, Fred?

03:50.000 --> 03:52.560
Yeah, Harriet, Nancy, Lorraine...

03:52.560 --> 03:53.960
Two Lorraines.

03:53.960 --> 03:56.120
How about a Hope? Hope Harcourt?

03:56.120 --> 03:58.600
No, but there was a lady came in
asking for you.

03:58.600 --> 04:00.640
He's wrong, Billy. It was only me.

04:00.640 --> 04:02.240
Reno!

04:05.160 --> 04:07.360
Oh, my God. We had a date.

04:07.360 --> 04:09.400
That's OK. I'd say forget it,
but you already did.

04:09.400 --> 04:10.720
Reno, I am so sorry.

04:10.720 --> 04:13.320
My boss is going to London
first thing in the morning,

04:13.320 --> 04:15.520
I had a thousand things to do
for him.

04:15.520 --> 04:16.960
I'M going to London in the morning,

04:16.960 --> 04:18.760
and all you had to do for me
was buy me a drink.

04:18.760 --> 04:20.040
What'll it be, ma'am?

04:20.040 --> 04:22.600
A martini, only make it with rye and
put a cherry in it

04:22.600 --> 04:24.760
instead of an olive.
Yeah, two Manhattans, Fred.

04:24.760 --> 04:27.440
You know, I'm getting worried
about you, Billy.

04:27.440 --> 04:29.520
I don't think this Wall Street job
is good for you.

04:29.520 --> 04:31.080
Hey, I'm making $35 a week!

04:31.080 --> 04:32.800
Yeah, but look at you.
Look at your coat.

04:32.800 --> 04:35.440
What's the matter with my coat?
It's got a fried egg on the pocket.

04:35.440 --> 04:36.720
That's an old school crest.

04:36.720 --> 04:38.320
From where? PS 88?

04:38.320 --> 04:39.760
You're in trouble, kid.

04:39.760 --> 04:42.680
If you keep acting like
a stuffed shirt stockbroker,

04:42.680 --> 04:45.120
you're going to turn into one.
Why do I put up with this, Fred?

04:45.120 --> 04:46.920
You're nuts about me.

04:46.920 --> 04:50.560
In fact, I've got a great idea.

04:50.560 --> 04:52.760
Why don't you come to London
with me?

04:52.760 --> 04:54.120
Reno, be serious.

04:54.120 --> 04:56.040
I am serious.

04:56.040 --> 04:58.280
England won't be the same
without you.

04:58.280 --> 05:00.760
Nah, guys like me
are a dime a dozen.

05:00.760 --> 05:02.400
You won't miss me over there.

05:04.600 --> 05:07.080
Why are the cute ones
always so dumb?

05:09.800 --> 05:14.800
♪ My story is much too sad
to be told

05:14.800 --> 05:21.080
♪ But practically everything
leaves me totally cold

05:23.280 --> 05:28.640
♪ The only exception
I know is the case

05:28.640 --> 05:32.000
♪ When I'm out on a quiet spree

05:32.000 --> 05:35.280
♪ Fighting vainly the old ennui

05:35.280 --> 05:38.520
♪ And I suddenly turn and see

05:40.840 --> 05:44.000
♪ Your fabulous face

05:46.800 --> 05:52.360
♪ I get no kick from champagne

05:52.360 --> 05:57.320
♪ Mere alcohol
doesn't thrill me at all

05:57.320 --> 06:02.960
♪ So tell me why
should it be true?

06:02.960 --> 06:07.840
♪ That I get a kick out of you

06:09.840 --> 06:15.400
♪ Some get a kick from cocaine

06:15.400 --> 06:20.440
♪ I'm sure that if
I took even one sniff

06:20.440 --> 06:26.600
♪ That would bore me
terrifically too

06:26.600 --> 06:31.360
♪ Yet I get a kick out of you

06:33.440 --> 06:44.840
♪ I get a kick every time I see you
standing there before me

06:44.840 --> 06:49.800
♪ I get a kick
though it's clear to me

06:49.800 --> 06:56.440
♪ You obviously don't adore me

06:56.440 --> 07:02.400
♪ I get no kick in a plane

07:02.400 --> 07:07.400
♪ Flying too high
with some guy in the sky

07:07.400 --> 07:12.760
♪ Is my idea of nothing to do

07:17.080 --> 07:33.040
♪ Yet I get a kick out of you. ♪

07:40.840 --> 07:43.680
Oh, hell, Reno, there's something
I've got to tell you.

07:43.680 --> 07:45.360
Yeah?
I'm in love.

07:45.360 --> 07:46.680
I'm in cabin 13.

07:46.680 --> 07:48.880
No, come on, Reno, not with you.

07:48.880 --> 07:50.320
I'm in love with a girl.

07:50.320 --> 07:52.120
God, she's fantastic!

07:52.120 --> 07:54.440
In fact, she is so fantastic
she won't even talk to me.

07:54.440 --> 07:57.400
That's why I can't go to London.
I've got to stay here...

07:57.400 --> 07:58.720
Oh, so that's it, eh?

07:58.720 --> 08:01.360
All this time, you were just
giving me the runaround?

08:01.360 --> 08:02.680
The runaround?

08:02.680 --> 08:04.440
You had me thinking
you wanted to marry me!

08:04.440 --> 08:07.360
How could you think that?
I always treated you with respect.

08:07.360 --> 08:09.400
Exactly. Did you ever
try and get me drunk?

08:09.400 --> 08:11.680
No. Did you invite me
up to your apartment

08:11.680 --> 08:13.080
to look at your etchings?

08:13.080 --> 08:14.720
No. We've been any taxi dozens
of times,

08:14.720 --> 08:16.000
did you ever once make a pass?

08:16.000 --> 08:17.200
No, not one lousy pass.

08:17.200 --> 08:19.600
You shouldn't have led me on
like that if you didn't mean it!

08:19.600 --> 08:21.280
Reno, I never meant to mislead you.

08:21.280 --> 08:23.840
The hell you didn't!
You never even laid a hand on me,

08:23.840 --> 08:26.080
and I'm not used to men
treating me like that.

08:43.240 --> 08:47.080
♪ I get no kick in a plane

08:51.160 --> 08:56.600
♪ Flying too high
with some guy in the sky

08:56.600 --> 09:01.880
♪ Is my idea of nothing to do

09:07.080 --> 09:21.120
♪ Yet I get a kick out of you. ♪

09:31.280 --> 09:36.280
♪ Oh, there's no cure like travel
to help you unravel

09:36.280 --> 09:39.440
♪ The worries of living today

09:39.440 --> 09:42.040
♪ When the poor brain is cracking

09:42.040 --> 09:43.920
♪ There's nothing like packing

09:43.920 --> 09:46.960
♪ A suitcase and sailing away

09:46.960 --> 09:52.520
♪ Take a run round Vienna,
Granada, Ravenna, Siena

09:52.520 --> 09:54.400
♪ And then around Rome

09:54.400 --> 09:56.520
♪ Have a high time

09:56.520 --> 09:58.480
♪ A low time, and in no time

09:58.480 --> 10:02.200
♪ You'll be singing
home, sweet home. ♪

10:17.800 --> 10:19.280
Excuse me, Captain.

10:19.280 --> 10:20.920
Has a Mr Eli Whitney come aboard?

10:20.920 --> 10:22.560
Mr Whitney is in the bar.

10:22.560 --> 10:24.800
I thought you kept the bar closed
till you sailed.

10:24.800 --> 10:28.680
He had a note from his doctor.
Oh. Thank you.

10:28.680 --> 10:30.760
Captain, Captain, a catastrophe!

10:30.760 --> 10:32.560
We may have to delay the sailing!

10:32.560 --> 10:33.800
What is it?

10:33.800 --> 10:35.280
Icebergs? A hurricane?

10:35.280 --> 10:36.480
Worse!

10:36.480 --> 10:37.800
Charlie Chaplin just wired.

10:37.800 --> 10:40.600
He's cancelling his berth
and sailing on the Mauritania.

10:40.600 --> 10:42.200
Good God!

10:42.200 --> 10:43.920
The passenger list, quick!

10:46.880 --> 10:51.040
Hope Harcourt, the debutante.
That's not bad.

10:51.040 --> 10:55.880
The Normandie has Jimmy Walker
and Machine Gun Kelly.

10:55.880 --> 10:57.320
Lord Evelyn Oakleigh?

10:57.320 --> 10:59.840
Nothing. Wealthy Englishman.

10:59.840 --> 11:02.160
Wait a minute!

11:02.160 --> 11:03.640
Napoleon!

11:05.600 --> 11:07.280
That's the dessert menu.

11:08.440 --> 11:10.240
Then we've got nobody!

11:10.240 --> 11:14.320
Quick, run down to the Stork Club
and see if anyone's left over

11:14.320 --> 11:16.480
from last night.
Aye, aye, sir.

11:17.880 --> 11:19.160
Would you just calm down?

11:19.160 --> 11:21.800
How can I calm down?
We're about to spend six days

11:21.800 --> 11:25.600
pretending to be something that
we're not, and why? Why?!

11:25.600 --> 11:30.640
So we can hitch a free ride on the
world's classiest ocean liner,

11:30.640 --> 11:34.000
that's why. And you think you're the
only person on this barge

11:34.000 --> 11:36.720
pretending to be something that he's
not? Half the passengers...

11:36.720 --> 11:39.120
Hey, captain,
where's the celebrities?

11:39.120 --> 11:41.680
This tab is deader than
the Flying Dutchman.

11:41.680 --> 11:43.880
Oh, fellows, please!

11:43.880 --> 11:46.720
My two stray sheep! Come along.

11:46.720 --> 11:48.680
Ah, the gentlemen of the press.

11:48.680 --> 11:50.760
I am Henry T Dobson.

11:50.760 --> 11:54.240
Not THE Henry T Dobson?!

11:54.240 --> 11:56.520
Are you serious, Captain?
Cut the bushwah.

11:56.520 --> 11:58.320
As you no doubt have heard,

11:58.320 --> 12:01.520
I'm on the way to the Westminster
conference where I shall present

12:01.520 --> 12:04.920
my two newest converts,
Luke and John.

12:07.520 --> 12:12.240
Luke here was a compulsive gambler,
who, as a reminder of his former

12:12.240 --> 12:14.480
shame, still carries with him
a deck of cards.

12:14.480 --> 12:16.640
And poor John
was a compulsive drinker...

12:16.640 --> 12:19.160
Reno Sweeney! All right,
now getting somewhere!

12:19.160 --> 12:21.720
I'll say. Hey, Reno, what are you
doing on board this tub?

12:21.720 --> 12:23.640
Same thing I do at my nightclub,
boys.

12:23.640 --> 12:26.240
I'll be saving sinners twice a night
in the ship's lounge.

12:26.240 --> 12:28.440
I see you brought
the sinners with you.

12:28.440 --> 12:29.960
Meet my angels.

12:29.960 --> 12:31.000
Purity.
Hi.

12:31.000 --> 12:32.120
Chastity.
Hi.

12:32.120 --> 12:33.440
Charity.
Hi.

12:33.440 --> 12:36.440
And I'm Virtue.

12:36.440 --> 12:37.920
Hi.

12:37.920 --> 12:39.640
The easy kind, no doubt.

12:39.640 --> 12:41.440
Say, brother, was that a pass?

12:41.440 --> 12:45.080
Miss Sweeney, I have no interest
in either you or your fallen angels.

12:45.080 --> 12:47.400
I'm ashamed to be seen in public
with you.

12:47.400 --> 12:50.160
How about a picture, boys?
Yes, please.

12:50.160 --> 12:52.160
If you could just hold there.

12:52.160 --> 12:54.040
Make sure to send a couple
to the Archbishop.

12:54.040 --> 12:56.600
Luke! John!

12:56.600 --> 12:58.840
Bye!
I tell you, boys,

12:58.840 --> 13:01.400
it ain't easy being New York's
most notorious evangelist.

13:01.400 --> 13:04.160
Come, who will lead this sinner
beside distilled waters?

13:08.040 --> 13:10.040
What?

13:10.040 --> 13:11.520
Which way to the bar?

13:11.520 --> 13:13.280
Oh, just through there.
Thank you.

13:13.280 --> 13:16.880
Oh, hey, girls,
give us the hallelujah.

13:18.000 --> 13:20.480
Hallelujah!

13:20.480 --> 13:21.800
Ooh!

13:21.800 --> 13:23.840
Hey, look! Hope Harcourt!

13:23.840 --> 13:26.960
Hey, Miss Harcourt, are you
presiding at the gold and silver

13:26.960 --> 13:29.400
ball this year? How about the
Newport cotillion?

13:29.400 --> 13:32.200
Gentlemen, my daughter's
debutante days are over.

13:32.200 --> 13:34.320
She's about to be married.

13:34.320 --> 13:36.800
Married?!
Yes, it's true.

13:36.800 --> 13:38.800
I'm marrying Lord Evelyn Oakleigh.

13:38.800 --> 13:40.880
We're getting married
at St Paul's Cathedral,

13:40.880 --> 13:42.920
and I'm very, very happy.

13:42.920 --> 13:45.360
Hey, Edith, how about a smooch?

13:45.360 --> 13:46.840
I beg your pardon?

13:46.840 --> 13:49.480
That's a kiss, your Highness.

13:49.480 --> 13:51.680
No! How marvellous!

13:51.680 --> 13:55.480
You know, I'm making a collection
of expressions you Americans use.

13:55.480 --> 13:58.680
"A smooch is a kiss."

13:59.800 --> 14:02.280
I say, darling, how about a smooch?

14:04.960 --> 14:08.520
Egad! Evangeline Harcourt!

14:08.520 --> 14:10.560
Elisha Whitney!

14:12.000 --> 14:14.080
Down, boy, down.

14:14.080 --> 14:17.160
Eli, you haven't changed
in 40 years.

14:17.160 --> 14:19.520
Me?! Look at you!

14:19.520 --> 14:22.080
You always did know
how to fill a girdle.

14:22.080 --> 14:23.560
Eli, really!

14:23.560 --> 14:26.440
Have some respect for the memory
of my late husband.

14:26.440 --> 14:28.240
Of course, forgive me.

14:28.240 --> 14:33.040
You know, if it's any consolation,
I was just coming out of

14:33.040 --> 14:36.280
the stock exchange when he took off
from that ledge.

14:41.480 --> 14:43.920
He jumped like a Yale man.

14:45.320 --> 14:46.680
Thank you, Eli.

14:46.680 --> 14:48.240
Boss, your passport.

14:48.240 --> 14:50.400
Oh, my gosh!
Eli, you know my daughter Hope.

14:50.400 --> 14:54.400
And this is her fiance,
Lord Evelyn Oakleigh.

14:54.400 --> 14:55.720
Her fiance?

14:55.720 --> 14:58.920
German word, Crocker.
It means they're getting married.

14:58.920 --> 15:00.760
I don't believe it!
I still don't either.

15:00.760 --> 15:04.160
And yet a week from now,
my little Hope will be a Lady.

15:04.160 --> 15:06.640
This calls for a drink!
Come along, everybody.

15:06.640 --> 15:08.320
Isn't Mr Crocker going to join us?

15:08.320 --> 15:10.760
No, no. He's got a date
down on Wall Street.

15:10.760 --> 15:12.720
Get going, Crocker,
and sell those shares.

15:12.720 --> 15:14.320
Yes, sir.
This way, my dear.

15:14.320 --> 15:15.600
Hope, wait...

15:17.960 --> 15:24.840
All ashore that's going ashore.
All ashore that's going ashore.

15:26.000 --> 15:28.120
Who is God?
The creator of all things.

15:28.120 --> 15:30.120
Where is God?
God is everywhere.

15:30.120 --> 15:31.680
And what does God know?

15:31.680 --> 15:34.680
Who's going to win
the Kentucky derby.

15:34.680 --> 15:37.000
You, have you seen a minister?

15:37.000 --> 15:38.240
A what?

15:38.240 --> 15:42.000
FBI. We're looking for a gangster
dressed up like a minister.

15:42.000 --> 15:44.320
You seen him?
Yeah, he went that way.

15:44.320 --> 15:47.240
Show us.
I've got to see somebody in the bar.

15:47.240 --> 15:48.680
Show us.

15:48.680 --> 15:50.560
Look, guys, I really don't have time
for this.

15:50.560 --> 15:52.840
Was it this way?
This is ridiculous. Come on.

15:55.080 --> 15:57.560
Psst! Moonie!

15:57.560 --> 15:59.400
The coast is clear.
Erma!

16:01.760 --> 16:03.160
Erma! Hey!

16:04.400 --> 16:06.120
Are we in England yet?

16:06.120 --> 16:08.240
Where's Snake Eyes?
He hasn't showed.

16:08.240 --> 16:09.600
To hell with Snake Eyes!

16:09.600 --> 16:12.280
Come on, he's public enemy number
one, he can take care of himself.

16:12.280 --> 16:14.560
Oh, my God, you don't suppose
the cops nabbed him?

16:14.560 --> 16:16.800
I've got to find him! Snake Eyes!

16:16.800 --> 16:19.040
Snake Eyes!
Quiet! Quiet!

16:19.040 --> 16:21.400
We're trying to make a getaway here,
OK? Mm-hm.

16:21.400 --> 16:22.800
Erma, just...

16:22.800 --> 16:24.720
Now look what you made me do.

16:24.720 --> 16:26.360
That's my "straddle various."

16:26.360 --> 16:29.160
Ah! A fellow cleric.

16:29.160 --> 16:30.920
No, I'm out of here.

16:30.920 --> 16:33.520
Allow me to introduce myself,
Doctor.

16:33.520 --> 16:35.320
The Reverend Henry T Dobson.
Yeah.

16:35.320 --> 16:37.640
Are you on your way
to the conference?

16:37.640 --> 16:40.360
No, I was thinking of
going to bed early tonight, OK?

16:40.360 --> 16:43.080
Oh, I mean the Westminster
conference.

16:43.080 --> 16:45.440
No, you see,
I'm not a west minister.

16:45.440 --> 16:48.000
I'm more in the east.

16:48.000 --> 16:50.040
What is your field, Doctor?

16:50.040 --> 16:51.640
Me, I'm a missionary.

16:51.640 --> 16:54.760
A missionary! Where?
Way out in China.

16:54.760 --> 16:56.520
Oh, I served in China for years!

16:56.520 --> 16:58.760
Oh, wow, that's amazing.

16:58.760 --> 17:01.200
Well, I wasn't actually in China,
I was more...

17:01.200 --> 17:04.560
Oh, I see, you were in Indochina.

17:04.560 --> 17:07.800
That's right, I was,
it was Indoor China, yeah, yeah.

17:07.800 --> 17:09.280
And you were...

17:09.280 --> 17:11.120
Outdoor China!

17:12.720 --> 17:14.240
That's so funny.

17:14.240 --> 17:16.960
Yes. We'll have lots to talk about.

17:16.960 --> 17:19.320
Sure.

17:19.320 --> 17:21.280
I'm sorry?

17:23.080 --> 17:25.280
You took the words
right out of my mouth.

17:25.280 --> 17:26.640
Hey, there he is!

17:26.640 --> 17:29.440
FBI! Gotcha, Moon.

17:29.440 --> 17:31.240
Unhand me this instant!

17:31.240 --> 17:34.120
I am the Reverend Henry T Dobson!

17:34.120 --> 17:35.840
Save it for the judge, buddy.

17:35.840 --> 17:38.320
Oh, my God, they're taking him away!

17:38.320 --> 17:40.560
He's gone! He's gone!
What are we going to do?

17:40.560 --> 17:44.120
Excuse me, captain,
is there a casino on the ship?

17:44.120 --> 17:46.120
Why, no.

17:47.720 --> 17:49.480
There is now.

17:49.480 --> 17:50.920
Luke, stop! What are you doing?

17:50.920 --> 17:52.920
We're going to end up in the brig!

17:52.920 --> 17:56.720
I just wanted to say
bon voyage to the lady, boss.

17:56.720 --> 17:58.760
You'll be saying bon voyage
to your job, Crocker,

17:58.760 --> 18:00.960
unless you get the hell off
this boat!

18:02.480 --> 18:04.200
I can find Snake Eyes anywhere!

18:04.200 --> 18:06.640
What will I do? He's my man!
He's my life!

18:06.640 --> 18:08.760
Erma, Erma, forget Snake Eyes!

18:12.080 --> 18:13.720
Final call!

18:13.720 --> 18:16.480
All ashore that's going ashore.

18:16.480 --> 18:18.120
You blew it, Snake Eyes!

18:18.120 --> 18:20.200
Now what'll I do with his passport
and ticket?

18:20.200 --> 18:22.480
Could you let me have them?
Who are you?

18:22.480 --> 18:24.440
Give him the goods, come on,
he saved my ass.

18:24.440 --> 18:26.160
Thanks a lot.

18:26.160 --> 18:28.000
"Murray Hill Cleaners."

18:28.000 --> 18:30.720
Murray Hill Cleaners?
Where'd he get a name like that?

18:30.720 --> 18:32.080
The Yellow Pages.

